description.value: A red siltware pottery jar of tall, narrow shape, modelled on the form of a situla, with a rounded base and a cylindrical neck. The top of the neck is missing. On opposite sides of the neck were two small pierced handles, near the top, but only one remains. The exterior is covered with a hard, polished red slip. On the inside clear marks of rotary production are visible.

description.value: A tall, narrow jar of coarse red siltware pottery, with a pointed base and sides which rise almost vertically, with a slight narrowing at the mid-point, to a rounded shoulder. From this they converge to a narrow mouth, which is surrounded by a low, external rim. The exterior of the jar bears remains of a polished red slip. The fabric contains a fair amount of grit and shows marks of burnt-out straw temper.

description.value:
Straight-sided cup with simple direct rim, 7.9cm in diameter, and angular carination to a recessed spot base. Covered with a cream slip on exterior and interior; decorated with a frieze indicated by two black painted lines below rim and three above base angle; within, red and black trefoil flowers. Pot incomplete. Fabric pink and tightly packed, some white, black and transluscent stones with flakes of red, likely Aswan ware imported from Egypt.
Adams Type A17 (1986, fig. 19).
